The MPs are elected through a system of universal adult suffrage and serve for a term of five years.
A Member of Parliament (MP) in Uganda is a representative of a constituency in the Ugandan Parliament. The Ugandan Parliament is the legislative branch of the government and is composed of the President and the Members of Parliament. Members of Parliament are elected through a general election and serve for a term of five years. They are responsible for making laws, representing their constituents, and holding the government accountable for its actions. The Speaker of Parliament is the head of the legislative branch and is elected by the Members of Parliament.
Boko Haram is a militant group based in Nigeria that seeks to establish an Islamic state in the country. The group is known for carrying out violent attacks against civilians, government officials, and security forces. Boko Haram has been designated as a terrorist organization by several countries, including the United States and the United Kingdom. The group's name, which translates to "Western education is sinful," reflects its opposition to Western-style education and its desire to impose Sharia law in Nigeria. Boko Haram's leader, Abubakar Shekau, has been known to make public statements and issue threats through various media outlets.

The Congress of the Philippines is the legislative branch of the government of the Philippines. It is composed of 24 members, who represent districts in the country and serve for a term of two years. The members of Congress are elected through a system of proportional representation, in which voters cast ballots for their preferred candidates. The party or coalition that wins the most seats in Congress forms the government, with the President serving as the head of state and the Prime Minister serving as the head of government. The Congress has the power to make laws, approve budgets, and impeach the President. It also has the power to investigate and impeach government officials, including the President.

It is composed of 12 districts and represents the people's interest in the legislative process. The members of the House of Representatives are elected through a system of proportional representation. Burundi is a small, landlocked country in East Africa, and has a history of political instability and human rights abuses. Activists in Burundi face significant challenges, including harassment, intimidation, and violence, but they continue to work to promote justice, democracy, and human rights. The Civic Group is a political party in Zimbabwe. It was founded in 2011 by Morgan Tsvangirai, who was the prime minister of Zimbabwe from 2009 to 2013. The party is a member of the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), which is a coalition of political parties that seek to promote democracy and human rights in Zimbabwe. The Civic Group is known for its advocacy of economic and political reforms in Zimbabwe, and it has called for the implementation of democratic governance, the rule of law, and the protection of human rights. The party has also been critical of the government's handling of the COVID-19 pandemic and has called for more effective measures to combat the spread of the virus.
The Police Force of Zimbabwe is the primary law enforcement agency in Zimbabwe. It is responsible for maintaining law and order, preventing and investigating crimes, and enforcing the country's laws and regulations. The Police Force of Zimbabwe is made up of various units, including the Criminal Investigation Department, the Traffic Department, and the Operations Department. The force is headed by the Commissioner-General of Police, who is appointed by the President of Zimbabwe. The Police Force of Zimbabwe has faced criticism for its human rights abuses and use of excessive force in the past.

The Head of Government in Panama is the President of the Republic of Panama. The President is the head of state and government, and is responsible for the executive power of the country. The President is elected by popular vote for a term of five years, and can be re-elected once. It also has the power to initiate legislation and to propose amendments to bills that have been passed by the House of Commons. The Legislature of South Africa is the law-making body of the country, consisting of the National Assembly and the National Council of Provinces. The National Assembly is the lower house of Parliament and has 40 members, each representing a constituency in the country. The National Council of Provinces is the upper house of Parliament and has 40 members, each representing a province in the country. Together, the two houses make up the Legislature of South Africa. The National Assembly has the power to make laws, while the National Council of Provinces has a consultative role in the law-making process.

Combatants of the Taliban may be involved in a variety of activities, including fighting on the front lines, providing support to the group's military operations, or engaging in propaganda and recruitment efforts. The Legislature of Russia is the federal legislative branch of the government of the Russian Federation. It is a bicameral body consisting of the State Duma, the lower house, and the Federation Council, the upper house. The State Duma has 45 members who represent electoral districts across the country and serve terms of four years. The Federation Council has 40 members who represent the constituent entities of the Russian Federation and serve terms of two years. The Legislature is responsible for passing federal laws, approving the budget, and impeaching the President of the Russian Federation.

The Legislature of Germany is the federal parliament of the country, consisting of the Bundestag (the lower house) and the Bundesrat (the upper house). The Bundestag has 299 members, each representing a district in Germany and serving a term of five years. The Bundesrat has 63 members, each representing a state in Germany and serving a term of two years. The two houses of the Legislature have separate powers, with the Bundestag having the power to pass laws and the Bundesrat having the power to approve or reject laws passed by the Bundestag. The President of Germany serves as the head of state and is elected by the Bundestag for a term of five years.

The name "Scotland Yard" is derived from the fact that it was originally located in a house on the north side of Whitehall, which was owned by the Earl of Scotland. The Metropolitan Police Service was founded in 1829, and Scotland Yard has been its headquarters since 1830. It is also the location of the police commissioner's office, which is responsible for overseeing the operation of the Metropolitan Police Service.

Argentina has a federal system of government, with power divided between the national government and the 23 provinces. Federal judges in Argentina are appointed by the national government and serve for a term of six years.
